ber":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Contributed by users","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/1.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/1.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"id":1},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}},{"id":205147,"mol_weight":0,"name":"T4 bacteriophage Gene 32 product","linfor":"","url":"https:\/\/eu.mpbio.com\/","sku":"SKU 11TGP32100","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"MP Biomedicals","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"link":"www.mpbio.com","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"id":226},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}}],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Klebsiella pneumoniae<\/span><span> (Kp) is of growing public health concern due to the emergence of multidrug-resistant and virulent strains. Taxonomically, Kp includes seven phylogroups, with Kp1 (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">K. pneumoniae<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;font-style:italic;\"> <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">sensu stricto<\/span><span>) being medically prominent. Kp can be present in environmental sources such as soils and vegetation, which could act as reservoirs of animal and human infections. However, the current lack of screening methods to detect Kp in complex matrices limits research on Kp ecology. <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>We designed a novel SYBR green real-time PCR assay, named the ZKIR assay, that targets <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Klebsiella pneumoniae<\/span><span> and closely related species (phylogroups Kp1 to Kp7). <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Based on 48 Kp representing its phylogenetic breadth, and on 88 non-Kp strains, the ZKIR assay detected all Kp and was totally specific for Kp, as no false positive was found.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">We also tested this method on spiked soil microcosms after a 24 h enrichment step (in Lysogeny Broth supplemented with ampicillin 10 mg\/l) and a short sample treatment. We showed that this procedure was sensitive enough to detect one single bacterium in 5 g of soil.  <\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1565705249}